keywords = "Flocking",
keywords = "Group size",
keywords = "Joining",
keywords = "Producer–scrounger game ",
abstract = "Many animals feed in groups and this has consequences when it comes to analyzing which foraging decision provides the best returns. In a group setting, the payoffs of a given action depend on what others are doing: the payoffs are frequency-dependent. Figuring out the best course of action in such situations requires game theory analysis. This article applies a game theoretic approach to two decisions that are specific to group foraging: why forage in groups, and why scrounge, that is, use resources discovered by others. Hypotheses for why animals forage in groups come in two types: antipredatory advantages and foraging benefits. I explore the main hypotheses for each type of benefit and question the traditional way of testing these hypotheses. The decision to join groups is approached as a group membership game where the optimal group size is often not a stable outcome. The expected stable group size is a negotiated outcome between group members and intruders, and depends on the extent to which group members can control entry as well as the genetic relatedness among players. The decision to usurp (scrounge) another animal’s resource is analyzed as a producer–scrounger game. The game is such that the scroungers’ payoffs are negatively frequency-dependent; they do better than producers when rare but worse than producers when common. The game has been modeled in terms of intake maximization as well as sensitivity to variance, and qualitative support has been provided experimentally. The article ends with a short discussion on the need to distinguish between evolutionary and behavioral mechanisms for reaching stability and points to the growing body of research devoted to the use of social information within foraging groups. "
}
